      <h2>Case 2: 90 days used</h2>

      <p>
        Patricia spent 90 days in Schengen (March 1 to May 29). She flew home
        on May 29. Her allowance is now zero. Her window contains 90 Schengen
        days.
      </p>

      <p>She wants to return as soon as possible. When is she allowed back?</p>

      <p>
        First of all, the window keeps rolling forward. On June 1st, a few days
        after returning home, the window still contains 90 days (March 1–May
        29). It will remain this way until late August, as her trip slowly
        drifts to the tail end of the window — or more accurately, the tail end
        of the window creeps up to the start of her trip.
      </p>

      <p>
        On August 28 a change occurs. The window on August 28 looks back 180
        days to March 2. This is the second day of Patricia's trip. March 1st
        is no longer included in the window, meaning the first day of her trip
        has just dropped out. She now has 1 day of allowance.
      </p>

      <p>
        The next morning, on August 29, the window looks back to March 3. Now
        both March 1 and 2 have dropped out. Two days of allowance. The
        allowance grows by one day per day, at the same rate the old trip ages
        out.
      </p>

      <p>
        She can re-enter on August 28 for a single day, or wait a few days to
        have meaningful room.
      </p>

      <div class="schengen-explorer" data-scenario="1" data-show-tabs="false">
