      <hr />

      <h2>Case 3: Multiple Shorter Trips</h2>

      <p>This is where the rolling window creates confusion.</p>

      <p>
        Four friends travel together in Schengen from February 1 to March 22
        (50 days). They all leave on the same day. Later in the year, each one
        wants to return to Schengen for as long as possible, but at different
        times.
      </p>

      <h3>Anna: returning soon</h3>

      <p>
        The first friend, Anna, wants to return in early May, just six weeks
        after leaving. Her new trip starts May 3. At that point, the 180-day
        window runs back to November 4 of the previous year — and the entire
        February–March trip sits squarely inside it. She has used 50 days,
        leaving 40 remaining. Her re-entry to Schengen is soon enough that both
        trips will fall within the same window completely. Since the older trip
        will not begin to age out during her second stay, and since both trips
        cannot exceed 90 days, her new trip is capped to a limit of 40 days.
      </p>

      <h3>Marcus: returning mid-window</h3>

      <p>
        The second friend, Marcus, returns July 15. On that day, the trailing
        180-day window runs back to January 17. His February–March trip is still
        fully inside it. He has 40 days remaining on entry.
      </p>

      <p>
        But as his new trip progresses, his earliest days from the February trip
        begin aging out. February 1 drops out on July 31 and on that day, he
        gains one day of allowance. February 2 drops out on August 1. And so
        on. Each morning sees one day freed, and because he is inside Schengen,
        one day used. This effectively freezes his existing allowance while the
        old trip ages out. By the time all his winter days have aged out (around
        September 18), his allowance hasn't changed for 50 days, and he can
        enjoy traveling on the remaining balance he has.
      </p>

      <p>
        What this means practically: even though his allowance is 40 days on
        re-entry, Marcus can stay much longer than 40 days.
      </p>

      <h3>Ilker: returning on the age-out date</h3>

      <p>
        Ilker returns on August 1st. This is 180 days after February 1, which
        is when the first day of the original trip ages out. He arrives with the
        same allowance as Marcus, and like Marcus, gets to stay for 90 days.
      </p>

      <h3>Olivia: returning after the window clears</h3>

      <p>
        Olivia waits until September 19th, 180 days after the group trip ages
        out completely. She arrives without any Schengen days in the window.
        This scenario is identical to Case 1, and like Patricia, Olivia can
        also stay for the full 90 days.
      </p>

